  <h2>It's Moving Fast</h2>
  <p>
    Every six months the landscape shifts. Some of it matters. Most of it is marketing. Here's what I'm actually paying attention to in early 2026 from a working fabricator's perspective.
  </p>

  <h2>Prusa CORE One L</h2>
  <p>
    This is the one I care about most, obviously. Prusa's flagship enclosed CoreXY with a build volume that can handle real parts — not just benchies and figurines. Active chamber heating, multi-material capability, and the same open-source DNA that made me choose Prusa in the first place.
  </p>
  <p>
    The L variant is the large-format version. For fabrication work — marine fittings, automotive brackets, enclosures — build volume matters. Parts that used to require splitting and gluing can now print as a single piece. That's a structural integrity win, not just a convenience win.
  </p>

  <h2>Bambu Lab's Expanding Lineup</h2>
  <p>
    Bambu keeps pushing speed and ease of use. The A1 series made multi-color accessible. Their AMS system works well. But the ecosystem is still more closed than I'd like, and repairability is a real question mark. When something breaks on a Prusa, I can source the part, read the schematic, and fix it. With Bambu, you're often waiting on their supply chain.
  </p>
  <p>
    That said — they're pushing the whole industry forward on speed. Klipper-based motion systems and input shaping are standard now because Bambu forced the conversation. Competition is good.
  </p>

  <h2>High-Performance Materials Going Mainstream</h2>
  <p>
    This is the real story of 2026. PPA-CF, PPS, and even PEEK are becoming accessible to desktop printers with enclosed chambers and all-metal hotends rated above 300°C. Two years ago these materials required industrial machines costing six figures. Now they're running on machines under $3,000.
  </p>
  <p>
    For 3D3D, this means I can offer aerospace-grade and chemical-resistant parts to marine and motorsport clients without outsourcing to industrial print houses. The material cost is still high, but the machine cost barrier is gone.
  </p>

  <h2>What I'm Watching</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pellet extrusion:</strong> Several companies are pushing pellet-fed systems that bypass filament entirely. Lower material cost, larger format, but calibration is still rough.</li>
    <li><strong>Automated post-processing:</strong> Support removal, surface finishing, and annealing stations are becoming integrated. This is where time savings actually happen.</li>
    <li><strong>AI-assisted slicing:</strong> Slicer software is starting to use ML for optimal orientation and support generation. Early days but promising.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The Bottom Line</h2>
  <p>
    The printers are better. The materials are better. The software is better. But the biggest bottleneck is still the same: knowing what to build, what material to use, and how to design for the actual conditions the part will face. That's domain expertise. That's what 3D3D is built on.
  </p>
